    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay so back to the science part. if the planets are in different orbits, why dont they always look like they are touching? does the tilt of the orbit matter for how close they look?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The tilt of the orbit does matter, and it's what prevents the planets from appearing to touch each other. The tilt of a planet's orbit is its inclination, which is the angle between its orbital plane and the plane of the Earth's orbit around the Sun. When two planets are in conjunction, their inclinations can either bring them closer together or push them apart, depending on how their orbits intersect.\n\nThink of it like a game of celestial pool, where the planets are the cue balls, and their orbits are the table. If the orbits are aligned at the same angle, the planets will appear close together, but if they're tilted at different angles, they'll pass each other by, creating a \"missing shot\" effect. The tilt of the orbit is what determines how close the planets appear to be, and it's what makes some conjunctions appear more like a \"close call\" than a direct collision.",
